osition, literature, rhetoric, literacy, and cultural studies share their experiences and insights as researchers, scholars, and teachers who centralize these concepts in their work. Reflecting deliberately on their own research and classroom practices, the contributors share theoretical frameworks, processes, and methodologies; consider the quality of the knowledge and the understanding that their theoretical approaches generate; and address various challenges related to what it actually means to perform this type of work both professionally and personally, especially in light of the ways in which we are all raced, gendered, and acculturated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAuthorshipxSocial aspects. 0aRhetoricxSocial aspects. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aEducation : Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 4aSociology : Ethnicity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aBabb, Valerie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBizzaro, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBizzaro, Resa Crane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlacio, Jami L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspinosa-Aguilar, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Ann E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrouse, Susan Applegate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Valerie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLogan, Shirley Wilson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c